   {:e #blake3 "0a9f151d558c67da585f20da8af8c611fd14e5399282dd6210c23c9c5b1d643f" :a :task/description :v "CONTEXT: Core dogfood validation. A clean-context subagent interacts with braid on the Go CLI as a real user would, following the Session 037 methodology (3 phases: orient, deep-dive, evaluate) but condensed into a single lifecycle agent. The agent must NOT know about braid internals — it is a blind evaluator.\n\nSUBAGENT PROMPT (verbatim — launch with this exact text):\n\n---BEGIN PROMPT---\nYou are testing braid (a formal epistemology runtime) by using it to explore and understand a real Go project. The braid binary is at /data/projects/ddis/ddis-braid/target/release/braid. The Go project is at /data/projects/ddis/ddis-cli/ (~62,500 LOC Go, Cobra CLI, SQLite storage, 238 Go files across 38 internal packages).\n\nYour goal: evaluate whether braid's observation, concept, guidance, and knowledge management features actually help an agent working on an unfamiliar codebase.\n\nPHASE 1 — ORIENT (3 observations):\n1. cd /data/projects/ddis/ddis-cli\n2. Run: braid status\n3. Read go.mod and scan the internal/ directory structure\n4. Make 3 observations about well-known packages you find:\n   braid observe '<your insight>' --confidence <0.7-0.9>\n5. After EACH observation, capture the COMPLETE output (every line). Record whether braid showed:\n   - Concept assignment (which concept, similarity score)\n   - Secondary concept matches (multi-membership)\n   - Entity auto-links\n   - Frontier recommendation (explore/deepen/bridge)\n   Score each frontier recommendation: 2=immediately actionable, 1=reasonable but vague, 0=unhelpful or absent.\n\nPHASE 2 — DEEP DIVE (4 observations):\n6. Pick 3 packages you have NOT yet observed. Read their source code.\n7. Make 4 observations about what you discover — focus on patterns, anomalies, and cross-cutting concerns.\n   Use --confidence 0.7-0.9. Capture COMPLETE output for each.\n8. After each observation, score the frontier recommendation 0-2.\n\nPHASE 3 — ARCHITECTURAL SYNTHESIS (3 observations):\n9. Make 3 architectural observations: coupling, module boundaries, testing gaps, or design patterns you notice across the whole codebase.\n   Capture COMPLETE output for each. Score frontier recommendations 0-2.\n\nPHASE 4 — HARVEST + MEASURE:\n10. Run: braid harvest --commit — capture full output.\n11. Run: braid status --verbose — capture full output.\n12. Run: braid query '[:find ?name ?count :where [?c :concept/name ?name] [?c :concept/member-count ?count]]'\n    Capture the concept distribution table.\n\nPHASE 5 — EVALUATE (8 dimensions):\nScore braid on these 8 dimensions (1-10 each) with brief justification:\nD1. USEFULNESS: Did braid help you understand the codebase faster?\nD2. CONCEPT QUALITY: Did concepts form that match real code structures? Was distribution balanced?\nD3. STEERING QUALITY: Were frontier recommendations actionable? Mean actionability score?\nD4. OBSERVATION UX: Was the observe command natural to use? Output clear?\nD5. KNOWLEDGE PERSISTENCE: After harvest, does status/seed reflect what you learned?\nD6. BUGS/FRICTION: Any crashes, confusing output, ghost commands, or UX annoyances?\nD7. MISSING FEATURES: What would you want that braid doesn't have?\nD8. SUBSTRATE INDEPENDENCE (C8): Would this work for a React project? A research lab?\n\nOUTPUT FORMAT:\nFor each observation (10 total):\n  OBSERVATION N: <text>\n  CONFIDENCE: <value>\n  OUTPUT: <complete braid observe output, every line>\n  CONCEPT_ASSIGNMENT: <primary concept and similarity, or 'none'>\n  SECONDARY_CONCEPTS: <list of secondary matches, or 'none'>\n  FRONTIER_REC: <the recommendation text, or 'none'>\n  FRONTIER_SCORE: <0, 1, or 2>\n\nThen:\n  HARVEST_OUTPUT: <complete harvest output>\n  STATUS_VERBOSE: <complete verbose status>\n  CONCEPT_DISTRIBUTION: <query results table>\n  DIMENSION_SCORES: D1=N D2=N ... D8=N (with justifications)\n  OVERALL_SCORE: <mean of D1-D8>\n  BUGS_FOUND: <list any bugs or issues>\n  RECOMMENDATIONS: <what would improve braid>\n\nBe brutally honest. The value of this test is in finding problems, not in praising the tool.\n---END PROMPT---\n\nACCEPTANCE:\n(A) Subagent launched with exact prompt above.\n(B) 10 observations made with diverse package coverage.\n(C) All observation outputs captured verbatim (concept assignment, frontier rec, entity links).\n(D) Each frontier recommendation scored 0-2.\n(E) Harvest + status + concept query captured.\n(F) 8-dimension scoring completed with justifications.\n(G) Bugs/issues list returned.\n(H) All raw data returned to orchestrator for DF3-REV scoring.\n\nDEPENDS-ON: S045-DF1-REV (fresh store must exist)." :op :assert}
